Personal interests and ideals, as well as a feeling of accomplishment, are examples of these internal forces. The feeling of personal pleasure or happiness that one receives from the activity itself is a common component of intrinsic motivation. The possibility of the employee being initially motivated to fulfill the quota by the prospect of the bonus should not be discounted. As a consequence of this, the worker may experience a decrease in their intrinsic incentive to sell, as well as their level of engagement in their employment. In conclusion, extrinsic motivation is a method of encouraging people to carry out particular tasks or to achieve particular goals, whereas intrinsic motivation is an internal factor that drives an individual to engage in a particular behavior, and it is frequently associated with a sense of personal satisfaction or enjoyment. Extrinsic motivation is a way to encourage people to carry out particular tasks or to achieve particular goals. 